Since $C$ is the incenter of triangle $PQR$, we have $\angle QRC = \frac{1}{2} \angle QRP.$  Since $\angle QRP = 180^\circ - \angle PQR = 117^\circ,$ we have $\angle QRC = \frac{1}{2} \cdot 117^\circ = 58.5^\circ.$

Also, $\angle QOC = 90^\circ,$ so $\angle QRC = \angle QRO - \angle CRO = \angle QCO - \angle CRO.$  Since $\angle QCO = \frac{1}{2} \angle QRP = 58.5^\circ,$ $\angle QRC = 58.5^\circ - \angle CRO.$

Finally, $\angle CRO$ is the external angle of triangle $QRC,$ so
\[\angle CRO = \angle QRC + \angle QCR = 58.5^\circ + 63^\circ = 121.5^\circ.\]Therefore, $\angle QRC = 58.5^\circ - 121.5^\circ = \boxed{-63^\circ}.$

Solution:
Let $s$ denote the semiperimeter of triangle $PQR$ and let $r$ denote the inradius of triangle $PQR.$  Then
\begin{align*}
\cos \frac{Q}{2} &= \frac{s - QR}{r}, \\
\cos \frac{R}{2} &= \frac{s - RP}{r},
\end{align*}so
\[\cos \frac{Q}{2} \cos \frac{R}{2} = \frac{(s - QR)(s - RP)}{r^2}.\]Also, $\angle QRP = 180^\circ - \angle Q - \angle R = 58^\circ.$  Then
\begin{align*}
\cos \frac{Q + R}{2} &= \cos \left( 90^\circ - \frac{\angle QRP}{2} \right) \\
&= \sin \frac{\angle QRP}{2} \\
&= \sin 29^\circ.
\end{align*}Hence,
\[\cos \frac{Q}{2} \cos \frac{R}{2} - \sin^2 29^\circ = \frac{(s - QR)(s - RP)}{r^2} - \sin^2 29^\circ = 0.\]Then $(s - QR)(s - RP) = r^2 \sin^2 29^\circ.$

